Scrolling through the comments and saw this. A day late, but I think it's important to mention that Cherenkov radiation is not common to malfunctioning reactors/damaged power plants in particular - it's actually just plain common to reactors, and sometimes even radioactive substances like cesium-137, which I would not recommend holding for too long.

If you look into a research reactor (ones used for power are pretty much sealed off completely, unless you need to do some serious maintenance) which is perfectly safe to do while it's operating because of how much water is between you and the fuel rods, you will see Cherenkov radiation.







